Dear Mennix-<br>
<br>
My pet has been acting listless and depressed lately. He doesn't cackle gleefully any more like he did when I first got him. It's actually more of a muffled whine now. I think it may be a sort of separation anxiety having to do with his complete lack of flesh and tissue but I'm just not sure. I haven't had him for very long and I'm not sure that I'm caring for him correctly. Can you help out a desperate Shadow Knight by offering some tips on how I can keep my pet happy and healthy? <br>
<br>
&quot;W&quot; from Qeynos, Human Shadow Knight of Bertoxxulous<br>
<br>
 <br>
<br>
Dear W,<br>
<br>
I am going to make an assumption here. You force your poor pet to fight monsters don’t you? Do you really think your pet wants to fight? I highly doubt it. Pets are companions. They are friends. Now, why do you think your pet is feeling so listless? I hope you are sincere in your desire to keep your pet happy and healthy. <br>
<br>
So, in order to have a party pet, one that will always be faithful and happy, I have created a &quot;How to Have a Happy Pet&quot; check-off list. I believe if you do all that I have listed here, your pet will once again smile, dance, sing, and just be the happiest pet in all of Norrath.<br>
<br>
&quot;How to Have a Happy Pet&quot;<br>
<br>
-Don’t use you pet as a weapon.<br>
<br>
-Feed your pet often. (If pet is a skeleton, feeding pet can be, uhm, not a good idea since the food will just slip through its bones.)<br>
<br>
-Talk to your pet. Encourage it. Praise it.<br>
<br>
-Give your pet presents. Do you really need that Ykesha? Wouldn’t your pet look better with it?<br>
<br>
-Never, NEVER, let your pet wander around a dungeon by itself. Dungeons are scary, and pets don’t like scary.<br>
<br>
These are but a few things you can do to ensure a happy pet. It is up to you to prove you are sincere. You have taken on the responsibility of a pet, so treat it right!<br>
